 nEvent URL: https://members.thequinhouse.com/events/169177\n\n1:00PM Progr
 am\, 2:30PM Networking \nTwo frontiers. One stage. Not to be missed. In t
 his high-voltage edition of 90 Minutes of Innovation\, flight becomes more
  than a metaphor — it becomes a stress test for the future of AI\, defen
 se\, climate innovation\, and human judgment itself.\n\nJohn Werner — ve
 nture capitalist\, Forbes AI columnist\, and Innovation Curator at The ’
 Quin House — convenes an extraordinary pairing you won’t see anywhere 
 else. A real-world Top Gun who has flown 80 combat missions\, 290 test mis
 sions\, and logged more than 2\,000 hours across 30 aircraft — including
  the F-35\, F-15\, and F-16 — operating alongside AI in live\, high-stak
 es environments. And a leader helping build one of the most highly capital
 ized electric aviation companies in the world.\n\nFirst: Kristen Costello\
 n\nBuilding the Next Aviation System\n\nKristen Costello is a pilot and ex
 ecutive at Vermont-based Beta Technologies\, a New England aerospace compa
 ny valued at more than $2 billion and backed by over $1 billion from Fidel
 ity\, Qatar Investment Authority\, Amazon’s Climate Pledge Fund\, GE Aer
 ospace\, and others.\n\nBeta isn’t pitching a concept. It’s building a
  new aviation system. Founded by former Harvard hockey player Kyle Clark �
 �� once told not to return to Vermont because “there was nothing there�
 � — Beta has grown into one of the most ambitious aerospace companies on
  the planet. The company is developing all-electric aircraft for cargo\, m
 edical logistics\, and passenger travel while simultaneously constructing 
 a nationwide charging network. It has completed cross-country flights\, se
 cured major commercial and defense partnerships\, and is advancing through
  the FAA’s rigorous certification process.\n\nThe breakthrough isn’t j
 ust the airplane. It’s the systems thinking — aircraft\, charging infr
 astructure\, certification\, pilot training\, and operations built in para
 llel. Not incremental change\, but a redesign of regional air mobility fro
 m propulsion to power grid. If it succeeds\, it won’t just change how we
  fly. It will change where flying makes sense.\n\nThen: Tucker “Cinco”
  Hamilton\n\nWhere Humans and AI Share the Cockpit\n\nThe evening shifts t
 o contested airspace.\n\nRetired U.S. Air Force Colonel and experimental f
 ighter test pilot Tucker “Cinco” Hamilton — former Chief of AI Test 
 and Operations for the U.S. Air Force and Space Force — led the integrat
 ion of AI-enabled autonomy into combat aircraft. He has operated at the ed
 ge\, where algorithms and humans share the cockpit in real-time\, high-con
 sequence environments.\n\nHamilton brings audiences inside moments few wil
 l ever experience: ejecting from a failing aircraft\, managing an engine f
 ire at twice the speed of sound\, crash-landing a jet while fighting to ke
 ep it upright\, and flying combat missions over Afghanistan. For Hamilton\
 , AI is not theoretical. It is airborne. He has confronted the defining qu
 estions of our era:\n\nWhen should a machine be trusted?\n\nHow do you tes
 t systems that learn?\n\nWhat happens when AI evolves faster than doctrine
 ?\n\nWho is accountable when autonomy acts?\n\nThis program also marks the
  debut of his new book\, Unlocking the Last 20%\, on elite performance in 
 an age of automation.\n\nAviation has always previewed the future. Now it 
 is revealing the operating system of the next century. The future is not h
 umans replaced by machines. It is humans redesigned alongside them.\n\n*Th
 is event is complimentary and reserved for members only. Light bites and r
